      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(providers): add experimental apple-vz provider for local Linux VMs",
        "body": "Fixes #262.\n\n## Summary\n\nThis PR adds an experimental built-in `apple-vz` provider for local Linux VMs on Apple Silicon macOS.\n\nThe provider is local-only, Linux-only, and keeps Crabbox's normal SSH-lease workflow:\n\n- `warmup`\n- `run`\n- `ssh`\n- `status`\n- `list`\n- `stop`\n- `cleanup`\n\nUnder the hood it uses Apple's `Virtualization.framework` through a small helper binary, then hands the guest back to Crabbox as a normal SSH target.\n\n## Why this is useful\n\nCrabbox already has nearby options, but there is still one gap:\n\n- `apple-container` gives a local Apple-native Linux container, not a VM\n- `apple-machine` gives a persistent Apple machine flow, not the normal Crabbox SSH-lease path\n- `multipass` gives a local Linux VM, but through Canonical Multipass instead of Apple's virtualization stack\n- `tart` gives a local Apple VM flow, but for macOS guests\n- `parallels` gives a third-party VM path\n\nThis PR fills the missing \"Apple-native local Linux VM with standard Crabbox SSH workflow\" slot.\n\n## Example use cases\n\nThis is useful for users who want to:\n\n- run a real Ubuntu VM locally on an M-series Mac with `crabbox run`\n- test VM behavior instead of container behavior, for example cloud-init, systemd, boot-time provisioning, isolated disk state, or guest networking\n- get stronger isolation than `apple-container`\n- stay local and offline, without cloud credentials or remote infrastructure\n- avoid depending on Multipass or Parallels for this specific Linux VM path\n\nExample commands:\n\n```sh\ncrabbox run --provider apple-vz -- go test ./...\n\ncrabbox warmup --provider apple-vz --slug apple-vz-smoke\ncrabbox status --provider apple-vz --id apple-vz-smoke\ncrabbox ssh --provider apple-vz --id apple-vz-smoke\ncrabbox stop --provider apple-vz apple-vz-smoke\n```\n\n## What this PR adds\n\n- built-in `apple-vz` provider registration and backend\n- new `crabbox-apple-vz-helper` binary for the Apple VM runtime path\n- config, flags, defaults, and `osImage` mapping for Ubuntu arm64 cloud images\n- provider docs and provider index updates\n- live smoke script support\n- tests for provider registration, config parsing, flags, and lifecycle logic\n\nThe helper currently handles:\n\n- host prerequisite checks\n- image download and caching\n- qcow2 to sparse raw conversion\n- per-lease disk cloning\n- NoCloud seed image generation\n- EFI variable store creation\n- VM startup with NAT networking and VSOCK\n- guest SSH exposure through a host-local proxy\n\n## Pre-submission hardening\n\nThis PR also includes the worthwhile lifecycle fixes found during pre-submission review:\n\n- cleanup on helper readiness timeout\n- specific handling for `stopping` / `stopped` readiness metadata\n- terminal handling for `VirtualMachineStateError`\n- VM stop request on local SSH proxy errors\n- top-level `workRoot` / `CRABBOX_WORK_ROOT` precedence preservation\n- helper `start --ready-timeout` wired to the provider bootstrap wait budget\n\n## Scope and non-goals\n\nThis stays intentionally narrow and experimental:\n\n- Apple Silicon macOS hosts only\n- Linux guests only\n- local-only, never brokered\n- no desktop/browser/code surfaces\n- no checkpoint/fork/restore flow\n- no Tailscale bootstrap\n\n## Important note on packaging\n\nThis PR implements and validates the provider itself.\n\nThe remaining follow-up is release/install packaging for the separate helper binary. Local source builds work today, but CI/Homebrew/release artifacts do not yet automatically ship `crabbox-apple-vz-helper`.\n\nI am happy to handle that as a follow-up if maintainers would prefer to review the provider implementation separately from release automation.\n",
        "branch": "codex/applevz-startup-runtime-fixes",
